# FeedbackApp

A feedback management tool for small product teams. Companies create a workspace,
invite their team, and share a public board where their users can submit feature
requests and bug reports. The team manages everything from a private dashboard.

Built as a portfolio project to learn the Next.js App Router and modern fullstack
patterns after years of Java EE backend work. The goal was to build something
real — not a todo app — using the stack that actually appears in job postings.

Live demo: https://feedback-app-eight-beige.vercel.app
Test account: demo@feedbacker.app / demo1234

---

## What it does

**For workspace admins**
- Create a workspace with a public URL (https://feedback-app-eight-beige.vercel.app/your-org)
- Create multiple boards per workspace (feature requests, bug reports, etc.)
- Invite teammates by email with admin or member roles
- Manage post statuses — Under review, Planned, In progress, Done
- Edit and delete any post in their workspace

**For team members**
- View and comment on posts across all boards
- Vote on posts and track what users are asking for
- Edit and delete their own posts

**For end users (no account needed)**
- Visit a public board via a shared link
- Submit feedback with just a name and email
- Vote on existing posts (requires a free account)
- Filter posts by status — most voted, planned, in progress, done

---

## Stack

Next.js 15 (App Router), TypeScript, Prisma, PostgreSQL (Supabase),
NextAuth v5, Tailwind CSS, shadcn/ui, Resend (email), Upstash Redis
(rate limiting), Vitest + React Testing Library (tests), Vercel (deployment).

---

## Architecture decisions worth mentioning

**Multi-tenant data isolation**
Each org's data is fully isolated at the DB level. Every protected route checks
membership — non-members get a 404 instead of a 403, so you can't even tell if
an org exists.

**Cursor-based pagination**
The board and dashboard both use cursor-based pagination. Offset pagination slows
down as data grows and breaks when new posts appear mid-browse. Cursors don't
have those problems.

**Optimistic UI updates**
Votes and status changes update immediately and roll back if the request fails.
Keeps things feeling snappy on slow connections.

**Public submissions without an account**
Users can submit feedback with just a name and email — no account needed.
If they sign up later with the same email, their history carries over automatically.
The signup flow detects the passwordless record and upgrades it instead of erroring out.

**Invite flow**
Invites use a signed token with a 7-day expiry. If the email already has an account
they're added to the org immediately. Otherwise a signup link goes out via Resend.
Tokens are single-use.

**Rate limiting**
Public submissions: 5/hour per IP. Signups: 10/hour. Uses Upstash Redis with a sliding
window. Returns 429 with standard headers.

**Role-based access control**
Three roles: owner, admin, member. Owners can't be removed or downgraded. Admins handle
boards, members, and settings. Members just use the boards. The sidebar hides links by
role but enforcement is in the API — UI-only hiding isn't security.

---

## What I'd do differently

Pass the boards list from the server layout into the sidebar instead of fetching it client-side.
Avoids the hydration issue and cuts a network request on every navigation.

Add Google OAuth. Most people reach for Google first and it's quick to add once GitHub is working.

Add an activity feed so admins can see recent submissions across all boards in one place.

Paginate comments on the post detail page — right now everything loads at once, which won't scale.

---

## Running locally

You'll need Node 20+, pnpm, a Supabase project, a GitHub OAuth app,
a Resend account, and an Upstash Redis database.

```bash
git clone https://github.com/guestFromAltair/feedback-app.git
cd feedback-app
pnpm install
```

Copy `.env.example` to `.env.local`:

```bash
cp .env.example .env.local
```

Fill in your values:

```env
DATABASE_URL=postgresql://...?pgbouncer=true
DIRECT_URL=postgresql://...
AUTH_SECRET=your-nextauth-secret
GITHUB_CLIENT_ID=your-github-client-id
GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET=your-github-client-secret
NEXTAUTH_URL=http://localhost:3000
RESEND_API_KEY=re_your-resend-key
EMAIL_FROM=onboarding@resend.dev
UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_URL=https://...
UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_TOKEN=your-token
```

Push the database schema and start the dev server:

```bash
pnpm dlx prisma db push
pnpm dev
```

Open http://localhost:3000.

Run tests:

```bash
pnpm test
```

---

## Project structure
app/
(public)/          — landing page, login, signup, public boards
(dashboard)/       — private dashboard, all workspace management
api/               — route handlers (REST API)
components/
layout/            — sidebar, topbar, navigation
posts/             — post cards, voting, status, pagination
comments/          — comment list and form
members/           — member list, invite form
settings/          — workspace settings form, delete button
lib/
db.ts              — Prisma client singleton
auth.ts            — NextAuth config
email.ts           — Resend email functions
ratelimit.ts       — Upstash rate limiting
types.ts           — shared TypeScript types
actions.ts         — server actions (signout)
prisma/
schema.prisma      — database schema